message.content: We find that $y=3-x^2+x^3$ and $y=1+x^2+x^3$ intersect when $2x^2 - 2 = 0$.  This gives us $x = \pm 1$.  When $x = 1$, the $y$-coordinates of the intersection points are $3 - 1 + 1 = 3$ and $1 + 1 + 1 = 3$, so the maximum difference between $y$-coordinates is 0.  When $x = -1$, the $y$-coordinates of the intersection points are $3 - 1 - 1 = 1$ and $1 + 1 - 1 = 1$, so again, the maximum difference between $y$-coordinates is $\boxed{0}$.
